# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: soap-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:soap-protocol/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP provides the Messaging Protocol layer of a web services protocol stack for web services.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] As an example of what SOAP procedures can do, an application can send a SOAP request to a server that has web services enabled—such as a real-estate price database—with the parameters for a search.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The server then returns a SOAP response (an XML-formatted document) with the resulting data, e.g., prices, location, features.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Since the generated data comes in a standardized machine-parsable format, the requesting application can then integrate it directly.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP evolved as a successor of XML-RPC, though it borrows its transport and interaction neutrality from Web Service Addressing and the envelope/header/body from elsewhere (probably from WDDX).
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP was designed as an object-access protocol and released as XML-RPC in June 1998 as part of Frontier 5.1 by Dave Winer, Don Box, Bob Atkinson, and Mohsen Al-Ghosein for Microsoft, where Atkinson and Al-Ghosein were working.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The specification was not made available until it was submitted to IETF 13 September 1999.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] According to Don Box, this was due to politics within Microsoft.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Because of Microsoft's hesitation, Dave Winer shipped XML-RPC in 1998.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The submitted Internet Draft did not reach RFC status and is therefore not considered a "web standard" as such.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Version 1.1 of the specification was published as a W3C Note on 8 May 2000.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Since version 1.1 did not reach W3C Recommendation status, it can not be considered a "web standard" either.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Version 1.2 of the specification, however, became a W3C recommendation on June 24, 2003.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] *SOAP* originally stood for "Simple Object Access Protocol" but version 1.2 of the standard dropped this acronym.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The SOAP specification was maintained by the XML Protocol Working Group of the World Wide Web Consortium until the group was closed 10 July 2009.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] After SOAP was first introduced, it became the underlying layer of a more complex set of web services, based on WSDL, XSD and UDDI.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] These different services, especially UDDI, have proved to be of far less interest, but an appreciation of them gives a complete understanding of the expected role of SOAP compared to how web services have actually evolved.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP specification can be broadly defined to be consisting of the following three conceptual components: protocol concepts, encapsulation concepts and network concepts.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] This is a set of rules formalizing and governing the format and processing rules for information exchanged between a SOAP sender and a SOAP receiver.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] These are physical/logical machines with processing units which are used to transmit/forward, receive and process SOAP messages.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Over the path of a SOAP message, all nodes assume a specific role.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The role of the node defines the action that the node performs on the message it receives.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] means that no node will process the SOAP header in any way and simply transmit the message along its path.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] A SOAP message needs to work in conjunction with other protocols to be transferred over a network.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] as a lower layer protocol to transfer messages.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] These bindings are defined in the SOAP protocol binding framework.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP provides a messaging framework only.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] However, it can be extended to add features such as reliability, security etc.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] There are rules to be followed when adding features to the SOAP framework.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] A collection of specifications regarding the semantics of SOAP header to describe any new features being extended upon SOAP.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] A module needs to realize zero or more features.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP requires modules to adhere to prescribed rules.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Represents the information being exchanged between 2 SOAP nodes.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] It is the enclosing element of an XML message identifying it as a SOAP message.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] A SOAP header can contain more than one of these blocks, each being a discrete computational block within the header.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] information is used to target nodes on the path.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] A header block is said to be targeted at a SOAP node if the SOAP role for the header block is the name of a role in which the SOAP node operates.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] is targeted only at the destination node which has this role.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] A collection of one or more header blocks targeted at each SOAP receiver.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Contains the body of the message intended for the SOAP receiver.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The interpretation and processing of SOAP body is defined by header blocks.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] In case a SOAP node fails to process a SOAP message, it adds the fault information to the SOAP fault element.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] This element is contained within the SOAP body as a child element.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] (Could be an intermediary or the destination node).
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The path consisting of all the nodes that the SOAP message traversed to reach the destination node.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] This is the node which originated the SOAP message to be transmitted.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] This is the root of the SOAP message path.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] All the nodes in between the SOAP originator and the intended SOAP destination.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] It processes the SOAP header blocks targeted at it and acts to forward a SOAP message towards an ultimate SOAP receiver.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The destination receiver of the SOAP message.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] This node is responsible for processing the message body and any header blocks targeted at it.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Both SMTP and HTTP are valid application layer protocols used as transport for SOAP, but HTTP has gained wider acceptance as it works well with today's internet infrastructure; specifically, HTTP works well with network firewalls.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP may also be used over HTTPS (which is the same protocol as HTTP at the application level, but uses an encrypted transport protocol underneath) with either simple or mutual authentication; this is the advocated WS-I method to provide web service security as stated in the WS-I Basic Profile 1.1.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] This is a major advantage over other distributed protocols like GIOP/IIOP or DCOM, which are normally filtered by firewalls.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP over AMQP is yet another possibility that some implementations support.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] SOAP also has an advantage over DCOM that it is unaffected by security rights configured on the machines that require knowledge of both transmitting and receiving nodes.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] This lets SOAP be loosely coupled in a way that is not possible with DCOM.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] There is also the SOAP-over-UDP OASIS standard.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] XML Information Set was chosen as the standard message format because of its widespread use by major corporations and open source development efforts.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Typically, XML Information Set is serialized as XML.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] A wide variety of freely available tools significantly eases the transition to a SOAP-based implementation.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The somewhat lengthy syntax of XML can be both a benefit and a drawback.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] While it facilitates error detection and avoids interoperability problems such as byte-order (endianness), it can slow processing speed and can be cumbersome.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] For example, CORBA, GIOP, ICE, and DCOM use much shorter, binary message formats.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] On the other hand, hardware appliances are available to accelerate processing of XML messages.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] Binary XML is also being explored as a means for streamlining the throughput requirements of XML.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] XML messages by their self-documenting nature usually have more 'overhead' (e.g., headers, nested tags, delimiters) than actual data in contrast to earlier protocols where the overhead was usually a relatively small percentage of the overall message.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] In financial messaging SOAP was found to result in a 2–4 times larger message than previous protocols FIX (Financial Information Exchange) and CDR (Common Data Representation).
[src:soap-protocol/soap] XML Information Set does not have to be serialized in XML.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] For instance, CSV and JSON XML-infoset representations exist.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] There is also no need to specify a generic transformation framework.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The concept of SOAP bindings allows for specific bindings for a specific application.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The drawback is that both the senders and receivers have to support this newly defined binding.
[src:soap-protocol/soap] The message below requests a stock price for AT&T (stock ticker symbol "T").
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Publishing a web service involves creating a software artifact and making it accessible to potential consumers.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Web service providers augment a service endpoint interface with an interface description using the Web Services Description Language (WSDL) so that a consumer can use the service.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Web services may also be discovered using multicast mechanisms like WS-Discovery, thus reducing the need for centralized registries in smaller networks.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] UDDI was originally proposed as a core Web service standard.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] It is designed to be interrogated by SOAP messages and to provide access to Web Services Description Language (WSDL) documents describing the protocol bindings and message formats required to interact with the web services listed in its directory.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] UDDI was written in August 2000, at a time when the authors had a vision of a world in which consumers of web services would be linked up with providers through a public or private dynamic brokerage system.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] In this vision, anyone needing a service, such as credit card authentication, would go to their service broker and select a service supporting the desired SOAP (or other) service interface, and meeting other criteria.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] In such a world, the publicly operated UDDI node or broker would be critical for everyone.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] For the consumer, public or open brokers would only return services listed for public discovery by others, while for a service producer, getting a good placement in the brokerage—by relying on metadata of authoritative index categories—would be critical for effective placement.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] UDDI was included in the Web Services Interoperability (WS-I) standard as a central pillar of web services infrastructure, and the UDDI specifications supported a publicly accessible Universal Business Registry in which a naming system was built around the UDDI-driven service broker.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] UDDI has not been as widely adopted as its designers had hoped.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] IBM, Microsoft, and SAP announced they were closing their public UDDI nodes in January 2006.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] The group defining UDDI, the OASIS Universal Description, Discovery, and Integration (UDDI) Specification Technical Committee voted to complete its work in late 2007 and has been closed.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] In September 2010, Microsoft announced they were removing UDDI services from future versions of the Windows Server operating system.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Instead, this capability would be moved to BizTalk Server.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] In 2013, Microsoft further announced the deprecation of UDDI Services in BizTalk Server.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] In 2016, Microsoft removed UDDI Services from BizTalk Server.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] UDDI systems are most commonly found inside companies, where they are used to dynamically bind client systems to implementations.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] However, much of the search metadata permitted in UDDI is not used for this relatively simple role.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] White pages give information about the business supplying the service.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] This includes the name of the business and a description of the business - potentially in multiple languages.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Using this information, it is possible to find a service about which some information is already known (for example, locating a service based on the provider's name).
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Contact information for the business is also provided - for example the businesses address and phone number; and other information such as the Dun & Bradstreet.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Yellow pages provide a classification of the service or business, based on standard taxonomies.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] These include the Standard Industrial Classification (SIC), the North American Industry Classification System (NAICS), or the United Nations Standard Products and Services Code (UNSPSC) and geographic taxonomies.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Because a single business may provide a number of services, there may be several Yellow Pages (each describing a service) associated with one White Page (giving general information about the business).
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Green pages are used to describe how to access a Web Service, with information on the service bindings.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Some of the information is related to the Web Service - such as the address of the service and the parameters, and references to specifications of interfaces.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Other information is not related directly to the Web Service - this includes e-mail, FTP, CORBA and telephone details for the service.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] Because a Web Service may have multiple bindings (as defined in its WSDL description), a service may have multiple Green Pages, as each binding will need to be accessed differently.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] UDDI nodes are servers which support the UDDI specification and belong to a UDDI registry while UDDI registries are collections of one or more nodes.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] SOAP is an XML-based protocol to exchange messages between a requester and a provider of a Web Service.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] The provider publishes the WSDL to UDDI and the requester can join to it using SOAP.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] The current UDDI search mechanism can only focus on a single search criterion, such as business name, business location, business category, service type by name, business identifier, or discovery URL.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] In fact, in a business solution, it is very normal to search multiple UDDI registries or WSIL documents and then aggregate the returned result by using filtering and ranking techniques.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] IBM modularized this federated Web Services Discovery engine in 2001.
[src:soap-protocol/universal-description-discovery-and-integration] The released technology from IBM is Business Explorer for Web Services (BE4WS) Archived 2008-05-11 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] In a web service, a web technology such as HTTP is used for transferring machine-readable file formats such as XML and JSON.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] In practice, a web service commonly provides an object-oriented web-based interface to a database server, utilized for example by another web server, or by a mobile app, that provides a user interface to the end-user.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Many organizations that provide data in formatted HTML pages will also provide that data on their server as XML or JSON, often through a Web service to allow syndication.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Another application offered to the end-user may be a mashup, where a Web server consumes several Web services at different machines and compiles the content into one user interface.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) is a dominant technology for Web services.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Developing from the combination of HTTP servers, JavaScript clients and Plain Old XML (as distinct from SOAP and W3C Web Services), now it is frequently used with JSON as well as, or instead of, XML.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Representational State Transfer (REST) is an architecture for well-behaved Web services that can function at Internet scale.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] A Web API is a development in Web services where emphasis has been moving to simpler representational state transfer (REST) based communications.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Restful APIs do not require XML-based Web service protocols (SOAP and WSDL) to support their interfaces.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] W3C Web Services may use SOAP over HTTP protocol, allowing less costly (more efficient) interactions over the Internet than via proprietary solutions like EDI/B2B.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Besides SOAP over HTTP, Web services can also be implemented on other reliable transport mechanisms like FTP.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] The term "Web service" describes a standardized way of integrating Web-based applications using the XML, SOAP, WSDL and UDDI open standards over an Internet Protocol backbone.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] XML is the data format used to contain the data and provide metadata around it, SOAP is used to transfer the data, WSDL is used for describing the services available and UDDI lists what services are available.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] A Web service is a method of communication between two electronic devices over a network.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] It is a software function provided at a network address over the Web with the service *always-on* as in the concept of utility computing.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Many organizations use multiple software systems for management.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Different software systems often need to exchange data with each other, and a Web service is a method of communication that allows two software systems to exchange this data over the Internet.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] The software system that requests data is called a *service requester*, whereas the software system that would process the request and provide the data is called a *service provider*.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Different software may use different programming languages, and hence there is a need for a method of data exchange that doesn't depend upon a particular programming language.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Most types of software can, however, interpret XML tags.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Thus, Web services can use XML files for data exchange.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] All of these rules for communication are defined in a file called WSDL (Web Services Description Language), which has a `.wsdl` extension.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] A directory called UDDI (Universal Description, Discovery, and Integration) defines which software system should be contacted for which type of data.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] So when one software system needs one particular report/data, it would go to the UDDI and find out which other systems it can contact for receiving that data.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Once the software system finds out which other systems it should contact, it would then contact that system using a special protocol called SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol).
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] The service provider system would first validate the data request by referring to the WSDL file, and then process the request and send the data under the SOAP protocol.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Automated tools can aid in the creation of a Web service.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] For services using WSDL, it is possible to either automatically generate WSDL for existing classes (a bottom-up model) or to generate a class skeleton given existing WSDL (a top-down model).
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Critics of non-RESTful Web services often complain that they are too complex and based upon large software vendors or integrators, rather than typical open source implementations.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] There are also concerns about performance due to Web services' use of XML as a message format and SOAP/HTTP in enveloping and transporting.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Functional and non-functional testing of Web services is done with the help of WSDL parsing.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Regression testing is performed by identifying the changes made to upgrade software.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Web service regression testing needs can be categorized in three different ways, namely, changes in WSDL, changes in the code, and selective re-testing of operations.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] We can capture the above three needs in three intermediate forms of Subset WSDL, namely, Difference WSDL (DWSDL), Unit WSDL (UWSDL), and Reduced WSDL (RWSDL), respectively.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] These three Subset WSDLs are then combined to form Combined WSDL (CWSDL) that is further used for regression testing of the Web service.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] This will help in Automated Web Service Change Management (AWSCM), by performing the selection of the relevant test cases to construct a reduced test suite from the old test suite.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Web services testing can also be automated using several test automation tools like SoapUI, Oracle Application Testing Suite (OATS), Unified Functional Testing, Selenium, etc.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Work-related to the capture and visualization of changes made to a Web service.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] Visualization and computation of changes can be done in the form of intermediate artifacts (Subset WSDL).
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] The insight on the computation of change impact is helpful in testing, top-down development and reduce regression testing.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] AWSCM is a tool that can identify subset operations in a WSDL file to construct a subset WSDL.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] While UDDI was intended to serve as a service directory and become the means to discovering web services, many vendors discontinued their UDDI solutions or repositories between 2005 and 2008, including Microsoft, SAP, IBM, among others.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] A key study published in WWW2008 Conference (Beijing, China) presented the state of SOAP-based web services and concluded that only 63% of the available SOAP-based web services at the time of the study were actually active or can be invoked.
[src:soap-protocol/web-service] The study also found that search engines were becoming an ideal source for searching for web services compared to that of service registries like the UDDI due its design complexity.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The **Web Services Description Language** (**WSDL** /ˈwɪz dəl/) is an XML-based interface description language that is used for describing the functionality offered by a web service.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The acronym is also used for any specific WSDL description of a web service (also referred to as a *WSDL file*), which provides a machine-readable description of how the service can be called, what parameters it expects, and what data structures it returns.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] Therefore, its purpose is roughly like a type signature in a programming language.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The latest version of WSDL, which became a W3C recommendation in 2007, is WSDL 2.0.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The meaning of the acronym has changed from version 1.1 where the "D" stood for "Definition".
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The WSDL describes services as collections of network endpoints, or ports.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The WSDL specification provides an XML format for documents for this purpose.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The abstract definitions of ports and messages are separated from their concrete use or instance, allowing the reuse of these definitions.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] A port is defined by associating a network address with a reusable binding, and a collection of ports defines a service.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] Messages are abstract descriptions of the data being exchanged, and port types are abstract collections of supported operations.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The concrete protocol and data format specifications for a particular port type constitutes a reusable binding, where the operations and messages are then bound to a concrete network protocol and message format.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] In this way, WSDL describes the public interface to the Web service.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] WSDL is often used in combination with SOAP and an XML Schema to provide Web services over the Internet.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] A client program connecting to a Web service can read the WSDL file to determine what operations are available on the server.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] Any special datatypes used are embedded in the WSDL file in the form of XML Schema.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The client can then use SOAP to actually call one of the operations listed in the WSDL file, using for example XML over HTTP.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] The current version of the specification is 2.0; version 1.1 has not been endorsed by the W3C but version 2.0 is a W3C recommendation.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] WSDL 1.2 was renamed WSDL 2.0 because of its substantial differences from WSDL 1.1.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] By accepting binding to all the HTTP request methods (not only GET and POST as in version 1.1), the WSDL 2.0 specification offers better support for RESTful web services, and is much simpler to implement.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] However support for this specification is still poor in software development kits for Web Services which often offer tools only for WSDL 1.1.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] For example, the version 2.0 of the Business Process Execution Language (BPEL) only supports WSDL 1.1.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] 2000) was developed by IBM, Microsoft, and Ariba to describe Web Services for their SOAP toolkit.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] It was built by combining two service description languages: NASSL (Network Application Service Specification Language) from IBM and SDL (Service Description Language) from Microsoft.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] WSDL 1.1, published in March 2001, is the formalization of WSDL 1.0.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] No major changes were introduced between 1.0 and 1.1.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] WSDL 1.2 (June 2003) was a working draft at W3C, but has become WSDL 2.0.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] According to W3C: WSDL 1.2 is easier and more flexible for developers than the previous version.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] WSDL 1.2 attempts to remove non-interoperable features and also defines the HTTP 1.1 binding better.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] WSDL 1.2 was not supported by most SOAP servers/vendors.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] WSDL 2.0 became a W3C recommendation in June 2007.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] WSDL 1.2 was renamed to WSDL 2.0 because it has substantial differences from WSDL 1.1.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] Subset WSDL (SWSDL) is a WSDL with the subset operations of an original WSDL.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] A developer can use SWSDL to access Subset Service, thus handle subset of web service code.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] A Subset WSDL can be used to perform web service testing and top down development.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] Slicing of a web service can be done using a Subset WSDL to access Subset Service.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] Subset Service can be categorized into layers using SWSDL.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] SWSDLs are used for Web service analysis, testing and top down development.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] Since WSDL files are an XML-based specification for describing a web service, WSDL files are susceptible to attack.
[src:soap-protocol/web-services-description-language] To mitigate vulnerability of these files, limiting access to generated WSDL files, setting proper access restrictions on WSDL definitions, and avoiding unnecessary definitions in web services is encouraged.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:soap-protocol/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:soap-protocol/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:soap-protocol/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
